latestPosts.caption:
You want healthy, beautiful hair.
You favor evidence based treatments over trends.
You invest in yourself.
You understand consistency is key to improve any aspect of your life. 
You are welcome to my profile. 

I'm Dr. Adri, a German board certified dermatologist specialized in hair and scalp diseases. 

I take your hair loss concerns seriously and will empower you in your hair health journey. 

Follow me for hair loss solutions, skin&hair care, and aesthetic dermatology with natural results. 🤗🪮

Never in my wildest dreams, did I think I would be going for my third university degree in Europe 🤓... this time on hair science 🪮✨, in Italy 🇮🇹... 🤯

I have a M.Sc. in regenerative medicine and worked in different research laboratories in Germany, where I learned precision, patience and manual dexterity. With a solid, scientific background on regenerative medicine, I am able to translate the biomolecular aspects of different therapies to the service of my patients needs. No bogus, no snake oils. Skin care, botanicals? yes, but only evidence based, I got your back. 

I also have a doctorate in medicine. I really invested in this degree and I wanted to get it before finishing residency (which I did in parallel). Medical doctorate candidates in Germany, who successfully defend their doctoral thesis, are awarded the degree of Doktor der Medizin or Dr. med.. They are very strict about the rules around this 😅, but interestingly you are allowed to include it in your personal identity documents so it becomes part of your name. 🤓 I did mine on the inflammatory role of fibroblasts in psoriasis, you can find the abstract in the Heidelberg University library archive online 😅

Follow me for more insights on my career path in 🇩🇪🇮🇹

7. Point out areas that "need" treatment that were not mentioned by the patient. This is a nasty tactic to make people insecure about a facial feature they probably hadn't noticed before. What a terrible way to practice aesthetic medicine, to make people feel like sh*t so they come back to you to "fix them". 
8. Push patients to buy treatment packages. Most dermatologic aesthetic treatments are a process and maintenance is a part of this process. I will not pressure you into getting treatments. If you need to think about it, I will notice that and recommend you take a calm decision at your own pace. 
9. Advertise with a prestigious brand but inject another. Yikes. See point 4. If you agree to a more economic product because of pricing, that is legitimate, but being misled by advertising a high-end product and getting something else is not. I only work with top brands, so we won't be having this discussion.
10. Charge per ml or unit. This is not the local market where you get potatoes on a scale and pay per kg. I am also not a pharmacy that sells botox or fillers. Pricing reflects a personalized treatment, my time and expertise in the concept of my beautiful practice. 
11. Limit my medical practice to the bare minimum some medical-insurance burocrat decided for my patient. I strongly encourage you to get informed about what exactly your insurance covers for dermatologic care. There might be a gap between what you get and what you actually need. You might be surprised. I was. 

-Adri 🎀🌪️

1. Do unnecessary tests or procedures to bump up the invoice for the insurance. The compensation offered by insurance is ridiculous, I do not work for the insurance. I work in the best interest of my patient. 
2. Inject in beauty or hair salons. A physician (in Germany) can only perform medical treatments and procedures in the premises of a physician practice which by definition has a permit extended by governmental authorities. The only exception to this rule is a medical emergency, which aesthetics do not form part of. Being a doctor costs us so many years of sacrifice and dedication, many seem to have forgotten this. Our profession deserves better, much much better. 
3. Botox parties, see point 2. Any aesthetic procedure should be treated with professionalism. There is a patient history, informed consent and hygienic measures. I cannot understand how that is supposed to work in the context of a party. 
4. Not discard or even reuse product rests in syringes by "just changing the needle". What the f. I'll show you the product, open it in front of you and discard the rest in front of you. 
5. Overdilute product. This is not only dangerous, as the product can migrate unpredictably, but also constitutes fraud. 
6. Discounts or promotions. This is not the Dollar Tree. Quality and safety goes hand in hand with time and investment. 

Like for Part 2. 
- Adri 🎀🌪️

latestPosts.caption:
Even for private insurance. Your doctor is very probably not being paid fairly for their services, which is why many physicians rely on high volume of patients. Higher volume, less time for individual patients. This inevitably results in lower quality of care. 

Even the concept that treating private insured patients is very attractive and lucrative is incorrect, private insurance will rather pay for dubious stool tests, than a 35 minute consultation with your doctor. If you come back with follow up questions within a time frame, the consultation will not be covered by insurance, which will cause a delay in getting your next appointment (there needs to be a gap as to how soon your doctor can see you again). 

Discussing treatment options in depth is not fairly remunerated by insurance, in many cases I have had to do it for free. A system that relies on doctors (specially female doctors) to do "what is right", at the expense of their own time, financial stability and health is not sustainable. Yeah, some doctors are a**holes, but many are just burnt out and bitter to be stuck in a system that does not center on patient care. 

If you would like me to share more of how I changed my career to practice high quality medicine in the sole interest of my patients' behalf, comment below 👇
